title: For Sale/Trade:  Ultimate .300 Blackout AR and reloading deal
postcontent:
I have a Bushmaster XM15 re-barrelled to .300 AAC Blackout, rifle has seen approx 100 rounds through it. Has YHM gas block/flip up front sight, Magpul fore end, Magpul sling, new Vortex Diamondback 2-7X scope on one piece mount.

Photos were taken befoer the Vortex scope was added, haven't taken any updated photos yet.

With this rifle comes a Lee Loadmaster progressive press, Lee dies with factory crimp die, powder measure, brass feed, small primer feed, etc. I also have a Harbor Freight chop saw with aluminum jig for cutting down .223/.556 brass to .300 Blackout, also including a CTS case trimmer and a Sheridan case gauge for .300 Blackout. I will throw in a couple magazines (uses standard AR magazines), and a hundred rounds of various reloads (for use as reloading components only, I cannot sell reloaded ammo), these include 125 grain TNT, 125 grain Nosler Ballistic Tips, and some 110 grain V-Max.

This rifle rocks! Easy to shoot, quieter than a .223 (you can load it suppressed to make it even quieter), everyone loves shooting this gun! I have two of these, and have loaded enough .300 Blackout to last me a while, and have since switched to a single-stage press. (progressive are great if you're loading a hundred or more at a time, I usually one shoot 20-40 per range session, so I have time). This rifle loves the 125 gr TNT's over 19 grains of Lil'Gun (please work up to this load, even through some are loading as hot at 21 grains), this round is very inexpensive to load for, you can catch sales on the TNT's online in several places for under $100 for 500 bullets. Powder used is magnum pistol powders, easier to find and uses 1/3 the powder of other loads, very economical to load for.

This is everything you need to start shooting .300 AA Blackout and converting your own brass and loading. Price everything out yourself, well over $2k invested. $1,500.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1974 Kawasaki G5
location: North of Springboro, IN, Lafayette, Indiana
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a 1974 Kawasaki G5.  Bought this last year and rode it all around this fall, but I start a new job in a couple of weeks and won't have the ability to ride to work like I have been.

I'm sure a lot of you, like me, learned how to ride a "real" motorcycle on something like this - more than a minibike, but small enough to let you get into those really far-reaching spots in the wilderness.  The bones themselves are in remarkable shape for a 40 year old motorcycle - a real survivor.  I wouldn't do anything more than putt around the yard on the current (possibly original) tires - if you're wanting to put it on the road legally (or have other needs) the headlight is not functional and will need replaced.  Past that, it's really up to you - you could mod it out, restore it, teach the kids to ride, or just go have fun! If I weren't changing jobs I wouldn't be getting rid of it, it would get the two abovementioned items and I'd be riding all over out here.. but I have to have a vehicle that can haul stuff, and this bike just isn't up to that task.

I have a clean Indiana title in my name for the motorcycle.  If there's any other questions I can answer, please let me know and I'll do my best!

postcontent: D-EVO stands Dual Enhanced View Optic, but what does this mean? The short answer is this: Leupold has paired a 6x20mm scope with a red dot sight to give the shooter an unobstructed lateral sight picture. This allows the shooter to choose between scope and dot, or use both simultaneously. The shooter can use the dot to get on target, then shift focus down to the magnified optic to take the shot with great precision and accuracy.

title: For Sale:  AIM Sports WML
postcontent:
For Sale

AIM Sports

Weapons Mounted Light

150 lumens

uses one 123A type battery

"Desert Gold Limited Edition"

A friend of mine got this 2 - 3 years ago from CDNN ( same as  http://www.cdnnsports.com/150-lumen-quick-detach-led-light-full-size-pistol.html  except for the color ) and had it mounted on his AR-15.  He just isntalled Magpul  furniture on his rifle, and the mount he was using does not attach to the Magpul OEM hand guards.

Also, the light appears to be designed for use with a pistol, because the switch was not very ergonomic to use with a rifle.


FYI:  The rear plate to the battery compartment came loose, causing the light to work only intermittently.  It was a pain to troubleshoot, because I had no idea that the rear plate was removable, and thought something was broken.  I spent a lot of time cursing cheap, made-in-China products, thinking this thing was broken, until I must have had an epiphany and screwed the rear plate tight (using needle nose pliers).  See attached picture.  Since then, it has worked fine, although you may want to loc-tite the threads to prevent the plate from coming loose under the force of recoil in the future.  Or at least be aware that the rear plate may unscrew itself loose -- knowing this will save you a lot of frustration.
